Years of low oyster harvests have waterman Bill Beck worried about the future of the industry.
Recently, disease-free oysters became available for harvesting, bringing hope to Beck and his family.
Despite dwindling oyster populations in the Chesapeake Bay, watermen are optimistic about the managed reserves.
Concerns arise over introducing Asian oysters to the bay, with some states urging further research.
The decline in oyster populations has led to challenges for seafood processors, who face a shortage of workers.
Efforts to revitalize the bay include creating a central financing authority and exploring new oyster species.
